---
// MOONS — Pluto's five known moons.
// Seeded issues:
//   * animated system image missing alt          (image-alt)
//   * moons table has an empty header cell         (empty-table-header)
//   * low-contrast caption text                    (color-contrast)
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Pluto's Moons" description="Charon, Styx, Nix, Kerberos, and Hydra — the five moons of Pluto.">
  <h1>The Moons of Pluto</h1>
  <p>
    Pluto has five known moons. By far the largest is Charon; the other four —
    Styx, Nix, Kerberos, and Hydra — are small and irregularly shaped. All were
    discovered between 1978 and 2012.
  </p>

  <!-- Animated system image deliberately missing alt (image-alt) -->
  <figure>
    <img src="/images/pluto-charon-system.gif" width="440" class="content-img" />
    <!-- Low-contrast caption (color-contrast) -->
    <figcaption class="muted-fail">
      Pluto and Charon orbit a shared centre of gravity that lies in the empty
      space between them.
    </figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2>A double world</h2>
  <p>
    Charon is so large relative to Pluto — about half its diameter — that the
    two bodies orbit a point in space between them, rather than Charon simply
    circling Pluto. For this reason, the pair is sometimes described as a
    "double dwarf planet."
  </p>

  <h2>The five moons</h2>
  <!-- Table with an EMPTY header cell (empty-table-header) -->
  <table>
    <caption>Pluto's moons by size and discovery</caption>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Moon</th>
        <th>Approx. diameter</th>
        <th></th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Charon</td><td>1,212 km</td><td>1978</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hydra</td><td>51 km</td><td>2005</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Nix</td><td>50 km</td><td>2005</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Kerberos</td><td>19 km</td><td>2011</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Styx</td><td>16 km</td><td>2012</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    The four small moons spin chaotically, tumbling unpredictably as they are
    tugged by the gravity of both Pluto and Charon. They are thought to be
    fragments left over from an ancient collision that also created Charon.
  </p>
</Layout>
